01-Simple models

Francisco E. Fonturbel

26/mar/2022

Anthropogenic effects on chungungo’s abundance

Here we will explore some anthropogenic variables as potential drivers of abundance change on this species

Let’s do some nice ggplots to examine our data before fitting fancy models:

Uhhmm… there is a trend in the two inferior panels, but error are too big.

Individual model

Although is not the best option, we will try to fit some glms for each individual predictor variable depicted in the plots above.

Models

To do this, we will use a Poisson GLMM, using site and sampling month as random factors.

## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: abund ~ people + boats + pets + algae + (1 | site) + (1 | month)
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 220.4
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.2770 -0.4762 -0.1117  0.5539  3.5694 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  month    (Intercept) 0.000    0.000   
##  site     (Intercept) 1.190    1.091   
##  Residual             1.021    1.010   
## Number of obs: 70, groups:  month, 12; site, 6
## 
## Fixed effects:

## optimizer (nloptwrap) convergence code: 0 (OK)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular

Well, it seems that none of our predictor variables are significant… Also, R warns us that we have singular fit (this article to solve that).

Let’s try some multi-model inference to examine the relative support of each variable to our dataset

##     (1 | month), na.action = "na.fail")

Well, it seems that all predictor variables have similar importance.

Following Ben Bolker’s advice, we can avoid singular fit by removing those random effects with a very litle contribution (in this case, month). Let’s try fitting a new model using only site as random effect:

## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: abund ~ people + boats + pets + algae + (1 | site)
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 220.4
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.2770 -0.4762 -0.1117  0.5539  3.5694 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  site     (Intercept) 1.190    1.091   
##  Residual             1.021    1.010   
## Number of obs: 70, groups:  site, 6
## 
## Fixed effects:
##             Estimate Std. Error       df t value Pr(>|t|)   
## (Intercept)  2.28809    0.47508  5.40750   4.816  0.00391 **
## people       0.01861    0.03950 61.89227   0.471  0.63917   
## boats       -0.06868    0.11303 61.43529  -0.608  0.54565   
## pets        -0.02384    0.14673 60.80042  -0.162  0.87147

Well, there is no singular fit now, BUT none of our predictor variables is significant (doh!)

A Bayesian approach

As we have a relatively small (N = 34) sample size, we’ll try now a Bayesian approach (based on Dimas’ code) to test the same but under a Bayesian framework based on Monte Carlo Markov Chains

## 
##  Iterations = 3001:12991
##  Thinning interval  = 10
##  Sample size  = 1000 
## 
##  DIC: 212.1277 
## 
##  G-structure:  ~site
## 
##      post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp
## site     1.927   0.1741    5.097     1000
## 
##  R-structure:  ~units
## 
##       post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp
## units      1.05   0.7042     1.45     1000
## 
##  Location effects: abund ~ people + boats + pets + algae 
## 
##             post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp pMCMC   
## (Intercept)   2.29642  1.08415  3.43559     1000 0.004 **
## people        0.01738 -0.06011  0.09440     1000 0.652   
## boats        -0.07226 -0.29013  0.14713     1000 0.560   
## pets         -0.02465 -0.31782  0.24226     1000 0.846   
## algae        -0.04857 -0.75138  0.79824     1000 0.880   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

OK, it seems that there is no effect at all, as both approaches showed consistent results.
